Exercises

2. Types of sets

Complementary sets: basic facts

Consider a set AA and a sample space SS.

  1. For set AA there is a complementary set, which has the name A′A′. Choose the best option below about A′A′.

    Answer:

    The set A′A′ ...

    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

    Complementary sets do not share any elements.

    STEP: Use the definition of complementary sets to choose the correct answer
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

    The question describes a situation with three sets: the sample space SS, another set AA, and the complement of set AA. A complementary set contains all of the elements in the sample space which are not in the original set. For example, if

    S={1;2;3;8;9}S={1;2;3;8;9}

    and

    A={2;3;8}A={2;3;8}

    then the complement of AA is

    A′={1;9}A′={1;9}

    Two things are always true about complementary sets.

    1. The complementary set will never include any numbers contained in the original set.
    2. The complementary set will always include all of the elements of the sample space which are not in the original set.

    The correct choice from the list is that the set A′A′ never includes the elements of AA.

    Submit your answer as:

  2. Which of the choices in the list is correct for the set (A∩A′)(A∩A′)? (Remember that SS is the sample space.)

    Answer:

    A∩A′=A∩A′=

    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

    This question asks about the intersection of sets AA with A′A′. Any set and its complement are like two sides of a coin: they are separate, but together they make the entire coin.

    STEP: Think about the intersection of the two sets
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

    Let's continue to use the example where S={1;2;3;8;9}S={1;2;3;8;9}.

    We know that A′A′ is the complement of AA, so this means A′A′ has all the elements not in AA.

    If A={2;3;8}A={2;3;8} then A′={1;9}A′={1;9}.

    We are asked about (A∩A′)(A∩A′). This is sometimes written as (A and A′)(A and A′).

    (A∩A′)(A∩A′) means the elements that are in AA and in A′A′.

    A∩A′={}=∅A∩A′={}=∅

    The correct answer is: ∅∅ (the empty set).

    Submit your answer as:

Complementary sets: identifying a complementary set

Consider this sample space:

S={1;2;3;4;5;8;9;10}S={1;2;3;4;5;8;9;10}

Here is a set in the sample space:

X={}X={}

Identify set X′X′. Choose your answer from the list below.

Answer: X′=X′=
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

The symbol X′X′ refers to the complement of set XX. The complement of XX must include every element in S which is not in XX.

STEP: List the values which are in SS but not in XX
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

In this question we need to identify the correct set for X′X′, which is the complement of set XX. A complementary set includes all of the elements which are not included in the original set. Another way to think about it is like this: a set together with its complement will always contain all of the elements in the sample space.

In this case, we have the sample space:

S={1;2;3;4;5;8;9;10}S={1;2;3;4;5;8;9;10}

and the set:

X={}X={}

To find X′X′, take the elements in XX out of SS. Whatever elements remain belong in X′X′:

X′={1;2;3;4;5;8;9;10}X′={1;2;3;4;5;8;9;10}

In this case, there are 88 elements which remain. It turns out that X′X′ contains all of the elements in SS. This is true because set XX has no numbers in it at all.

The correct choice from the list is: {1;2;3;4;5;8;9;10}{1;2;3;4;5;8;9;10}.

Submit your answer as:

Complementary sets: working with set notation

Consider the following sample space:

S={s:s∈ℕ,s<10}S={s:s∈N,s<10}

  1. How many elements are in SS?

    Answer: The number of elements in SS is .
    numeric
    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

    What is the smallest number in SS? What is the largest number in SS? If you know that, you can figure out how many elements are in the set.

    STEP: Write out the elements in the set to determine how many there are
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

    We have the set

    S={s:s∈ℕ,s<10}S={s:s∈N,s<10}

    and we need to figure out how many elements are in it. This means we need to find out how many numbers are in the set.

    We need to interpret the set given to find out what numbers belong in the set. First, notice that the elements of SS are natural numbers because "s∈ℕs∈N". This alone means that the values come from:

    ℕ={1;2;3;4…}N={1;2;3;4…}

    But set SS also says that s<10s<10. This means that set SS only includes numbers in ℕN which are less than 1010. So the sample space, set SS, includes these numbers:

    S={1;2;3;4;5;6;7;8;9}S={1;2;3;4;5;6;7;8;9}

    Now count the numbers in the set to get the answer. We can see clearly that there are 99 numbers in set SS.

    There are 99 elements in SS.

    Submit your answer as:

  2. Within the sample space of set SS, suppose there is a set:

    X={5;6;9}X={5;6;9}

    Give any element in X′X′. If there are no elements in X′X′ write none in the answer box.

    INSTRUCTION: You should enter a single number from X′X′ or the word none.
    Answer: One of the elements in X′X′ is: .
    one-of
    type(numeric.noerror)
    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

    The symbol X′X′ refers to the complement of set XX with respect to the sample space in Question 11.

    STEP: Determine the complement of set XX and pick one of its values for the answer
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

    The question shows us set XX, which is a subset of the sample space SS. We need to identify an element which is in X′X′, which is the complement of XX. The complement of a set includes all of the values from the sample space which are not in that set.

    We can answer this question by comparing the list in Question 11 to set XX. The complement of XX includes all of the numbers in SS which are not in XX.

    S={1;2;3;4;5;6;7;8;9}andX={5;6;9}S={1;2;3;4;5;6;7;8;9}andX={5;6;9}

    Comparing these sets, we can see that the complement of XX includes these 66 numbers:

    X′={1;2;3;4;7;8}X′={1;2;3;4;7;8}

    Therefore, any one of the following numbers is an acceptable answer: 1 ; 2 ; 3 ; 4 ; 7 ; 8.

    Submit your answer as:

Key misconception: set membership with overlapping sets

[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

Which of these numbers should we use? To know, we must be aware of the following different statements in probability:

  1. Set AA only means the outcomes which are in Set AA but not in any other set.
  2. Set AA means every outcome in Set AA, even if they happen to be in another set.

We want the second case listed above. On the Venn diagram, Set AA looks like this:

We can see that Set AA contains two numbers. We need to add those numbers because we want all the outcomes in Set AA even if they happen to be in another set too.

Here are some examples to help show the impact of the word only:

  • Number of outcomes in AA only =4=4
  • Number of outcomes in AA =4+6=10=4+6=10
  • Number of outcomes in BB only =2=2
  • Number of outcomes in BB =2+6=8=2+6=8

The number of outcomes in Set AA is 1010.

Key misconception: set membership with overlapping sets

The Venn diagram below shows Sets AA and BB in the sample space SS. There are four numbers labelled on the diagram. They represent the number of outcomes in each region. For example, there are 33 different outcomes which are in neither Set AA nor Set BB.

Answer:

How many outcomes are there in Set AA?

HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

First you need to identify the correct region on the diagram for Set AA. Then you can read off the number of outcomes included in that region.

STEP: Identify the correct region on the diagram and then read off the number of outcomes
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

We need to determine the number of outcomes which are in Set AA. There are two numbers inside of Set AA's circle: the 44 is in Set AA but outside of Set BB. And the 88 is in both Set AA and Set BB. Which of these numbers should we use? To know, we must be aware of the following different statements in probability:

  1. Set AA only means the outcomes which are in Set AA but not in any other set.
  2. Set AA means every outcome in Set AA, even if they happen to be in another set.

We want the second case listed above. On the Venn diagram, Set AA looks like this:

We can see that Set AA contains two numbers. We need to add those numbers because we want all the outcomes in Set AA even if they happen to be in another set too.

Here are some examples to help show the impact of the word only:

  • Number of outcomes in AA only =4=4
  • Number of outcomes in AA =4+8=12=4+8=12
  • Number of outcomes in BB only =1=1
  • Number of outcomes in BB =1+8=9=1+8=9

The number of outcomes in Set AA is 1212.

Completing a Venn diagram

A teacher surveys a group of students. The teacher asks each student if they like to drink Iron Brew, Coke, both Iron Brew and Coke, or neither. The diagram below summarises the results, but there is one number missing.

Determine the missing number, nn, using these three facts:

  • 77 students like Iron Brew.
  • 1111 students like Coke.
  • 22 students do not like Iron Brew or Coke.
Answer: n=n=
numeric
HINT: <no title>
[−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

You need to use the first fact in the list:

  • 77 students like Iron Brew.

This means there are 77 students in total in the circle labelled Iron Brew.

STEP: Use the first fact given to find nn
[−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

We need to determine the value of nn, which is missing from the Venn diagram. nn represents the number of students who like Iron Brew but do not like Coke.

We can find nn using the first fact from the list. It tells us the total number of students who like Iron Brew. That means the total number of students in the Iron Brew circle must be 77. The diagram already shows 44 of those students in that circle. So the missing number must be the rest of the 77 students.

n+4n=7=3n+4=7n=3

The completed diagram is:

NOTE:

Statements like the first two facts in this question often cause confusion. For example, in this solution we used the first statement. People often incorrectly think that this statement means there are 77 students who like only Iron Brew. But that is not correct. You must be careful to distinguish between these two statements. For the Iron Brew circle in the diagram, these statements are both true:

  • 77 students like Iron Brew.
  • 33 students like Iron Brew only.

The correct answer is n=3n=3.

Reading a Venn diagram

In a group of 2020 people, someone decided to count how many of the people have a left ear and how many people have a right ear. The Venn diagram below shows the results. Set LELE includes everyone with a left ear. Set RERE includes everyone with a right ear.

  1. How many of the people have a left ear?

    Answer: The number of people who have a left ear is .
    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

    Find the parts of the diagram which shows the people who have a left ear.

    STEP: Find the correct region on the diagram and read the answer
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

    We need to determine how many people have a left ear. To do that, we must find the region of the diagram which shows the people who have a left ear.

    The diagram shows two circles. The circle labelled LELE represents the people with left ears. People who have left ears are counted in this circle. The other circle, labelled RERE, represents the people with right ears. People who have right ears are counted in this circle. The overlapping area is where we should count people who have ears on both sides.

    In this case, the region is the entire circle labelled LELE.

    There are two numbers in the circle. We need to add them to get the answer because we want the total number of people who have a left ear.

    The number of people who have a left ear is 2020.

    Submit your answer as:

  2. The two zeroes highlighted below make sense. Why should we expect zeroes in these regions of the diagram?

    A Some of the people were not counted.
    B The zeroes are for the people who have lost their ears.
    C They are wrong: the zeroes should be 2020.
    D People usually have two ears.
    Answer: The reason is choice .
    HINT: <no title>
    [−0 points ⇒ 1 / 1 points left]

    Think about the situation: do you know many people with fewer than two ears?

    STEP: Figure out what the zeroes tell you
    [−1 point ⇒ 0 / 1 points left]

    We need to determine what the highlighted zeroes mean.

    One of the zeroes in this diagram lives in LELE and the other lives in RERE. Does this mean that no one has any ears? No, it does not. The zero on the left side tells us that there are no people who have left ears but not right ears. And the zero on the right side tells us there are no people who have a right ear but no left ear. That is why all 2020 people are represented where the two circles overlap.

    The correct explanation for the zeroes is people usually have two ears, which is choice D.
